nova/virt/hardware.py.message:
You can use real type annotations now, since this is Python 3 only code. I think it would be:

  def get_pinned_cpu_constraint(
      flavor: 'objects.Flavor',
  ) -> ty.Set[int]:

i.e. flavor is of type 'objects.Flavor' (you need the quotes to delay interpretation) and it returns a set of ints. You'll also need to add this import at the top of the file:

  import typing as ty

tasks/ceph_get_keyrings_from_files.yml.message:
The way this task nests jinja tags is not valid and shouldn't work. But I'll suggest a different approach instead. Rather than setting a large number of vars (one per client key) you could set them all into a single dict.

set_fact:
  ceph_client_keys: |-
    {% set _keys = [] %}
    {% for client in ceph_client_filtered_clients %}
    {%   set _ = _keys.update({
            client: lookup('file', ceph_keyrings_dir ~ '/' ~ item ~ '.keyring')
        })
    %}
    {% endfor %}
    {{ _keys }}
